title: AI Don't Think That's a Good Idea

### Alexa, Play Despacito

It's safe to say that my mother is a paranoid woman when it comes to technology. Several cases of identity theft have left her traumatized, a woman willing to take absolutely no chances. Unfortunately, I seem to have inherited some of this paranoia. For example, a common thing for American tourists to do when traveling in Europe is to use location services to check out the foreign Netflix selection. Meanwhile, when my parents and I travel, the phone is on airplane mode for the duration of the trip, lest a hacker attempt to steal pesonal information from our phones over public wifi. No international Netflix for me. 

However, when the Amazon Echo came out, I was filled with both envy and wariness. Many of my friends blindly trusted Alexa, an AI developed by Amazon and (ab)used by people everywhere. Alexa began to seep into everyday life, perhaps even to the extent that Apple's Siri did. Alexa was in dorm rooms, kitchens, headphones, doorbells, and home security systems. Alexa even found her way into mainstream meme culture.

Once she sunk her claws in and made society dangerously dependent on her for their music consumption and basic everyday functions, there was no turning back. It's safe to say Alexa is here to stay.

### Intelligence Isn't Always Smart

While artificial intelligence may be taking its orders from humans, it may not always have humans' best interests at heart. No matter how hard we try to make AI systems think like humans, they never will. Even humans can't code how humans think, so how can AI code how humans think? How can humans code AI to be more human? 

If you really want to feel terrible about yourself, check out the [Moral Machine](https://www.moralmachine.net/) at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology Media Lab. Go on, I dare you. Here, visitors to the site are presented with a series of moral conundrums. It's similar to the exercises many students in high school psychology classes are given. On the [Moral Machine](https://www.moralmachine.net/) homepage, it says,
> "Welcome to the Moral Machine! A platform for gathering a human perspective on moral decisions made by machine intelligence, such as self-driving cars.

> We show you moral dilemmas, where a driverless car must choose the lesser of two evils, such as killing two passengers or five pedestrians. As an outside observer, you judge which outcome you think is more acceptable. You can then see how your responses compare with those of other people.

On their About page, Moral Machine continues to elaborate, saying, 
> "From self-driving cars on public roads to self-piloting reusable rockets landing on self-sailing ships, machine intelligence is supporting or entirely taking over ever more complex human activities at an ever increasing pace. The greater autonomy given machine intelligence in these roles can result in situations where they have to make autonomous choices involving human life and limb. This calls for not just a clearer understanding of how humans make such choices, but also a clearer understanding of how humans perceive machine intelligence making such choices."

Here are some examples of the scenarios [Moral Machine](https://www.moralmachine.net/) will throw your way.

In most cases, the people's votes are split. It seems that no one can really decide on what is the morally superior, and therfore human, choice.

Recently, Teslas have been increasingly purchased by YouTubers. They start filming their videos and set their cars to "autopilot." Of course, autopilot technology in cars is still not there yet, so right now it's mostly a combination of automatically staying within lines, braking when a car in front of yours brakes, and cruise control. While it may seem like nothing more than a frivolous toy reserved for only the wealthy, but it does bring the MIT Moral Machine test to life. What happens when we allow ourselves to be ushered along by automated cars in an unautomated world? What happens when we put an AI behind the wheel?

Do you trust a novice software with your life? Your family's lives? A stranger's life?

### No Need to Ring, Come on In

Amazon could not stop at simple devices when it came to Alexa. Now, Amazon owns Ring LLC, a home security company. Because the world was not complete until your doorbell was Alexa compatible. Ring LLC outfits your house not only with a camera doorbell to watch the outside world with an unblinking eye, but it also turns that eye inward with additional cameras in the interior of your home. Teenagers will get away with sneaking out or not doing their homework. The Eye of Sauron of home security has arrived.

Except...

There have been cases of Ring being used for evil. In one instance, a man hacked a Ring security camera to watch and talk to an 8-year-old girl in her bedroom. In another, someone hacked a Ring camera to racially abuse a 15-year-old boy in his home ([NBC News](https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/man-hacks-ring-camera-8-year-old-girl-s-bedroom-n1100586)). People always say, "You never know what goes on behind closed doors." Well, now thanks to Ring, you can. Ring opens every closed door to anyone who cares to look.

### What Kind of Corpus Even is This?

Even with those hacks aside, the algorithms from Alexa devices are a complete mystery to their consumers. Every request for Alexa to play "Despacito" is data. Every "Alexa, what's the weather forecast for today" is data. This data is being compiled into a corpus. In [Anatomy of an AI System](https://anatomyof.ai/) by Kate Crawford and Vladan Joler, they say, 
> "But they are also a resource, as their voice commands are collected, analyzed and retained for the purposes of building an ever-larger corpus of human voices and instructions. And they provide labor, as they continually perform the valuable service of contributing feedback mechanisms regarding the accuracy, usefulness, and overall quality of Alexas replies. They are, in essence, helping to train the neural networks within Amazons infrastructural stack."

If Alexa is constantly storing her users' information and using it to grow nefariously more powerful, is she really becoming smarter in a way that imitates human intelligence? Or is she only becoming smarter for the small portion of the human race who can afford to have Alexa blabbering out of every souped up electrical socket in their house? Is MIT's Moral Machine only collecting morality data from those who can afford to assert their opinions via an internet connection? Could those hackers who hacked Ring access the corpus, and did their hacking in some way alter the corpus for the worse? By building a corpus from the commands of those who can afford to give commands, is Alexa veering further away from human intelligence?

Well, I guess Alexa has never claimed to be human. Artificial all the way. Go big or go home.

### I Guess I'm a Conspiracy Theorist

All of this is to say that I, along with many other people, question the validity of introducing AI into people's everyday lives in order to make machines smarter. I think that for one thing, it creates a biased machine. Secondly, we never get to see our data again. Once we've been used as guinea pigs in the AI experiment, our data gives machines (and the analysts/programmers behind those machines) uncomfortable insights into our everyday lives. How much of the Ring security camera footage is unencrypted and looked through? Eventually, there will be an end to privacy. I think it has already begun. Amazon claims its Ring doorbells cannot recognize faces, but it's impossible to know to what extent that is true. AI may be trying to become more intelligent, but the only way for it to do so is to watch. Carefully. It must open all your doors. And it doesn't even have to ring a doorbell.
